    <h3>Translation notes</h3>
    <p>All examples use classical probability (effects are functions to [0,1], states are finite distributions). Cho and Jacobs work in the general setting of effectus categories, which includes quantum probability (effects are positive operators bounded by the identity, states are density matrices). For example, the Born rule on this page computes an expected value via a weighted sum. In the quantum case, the same pairing is tr(ρE), the trace of a density matrix times a positive operator. The pairing structure is identical. The algebraic setting (commutative vs non-commutative) is not.</p>
    <p>Every example is <strong class="text-green-400">Simplified</strong>: classical stand-ins for a framework that covers both classical and quantum.</p>

    <div class="bg-zinc-800 rounded-lg p-4 text-center text-sm text-gray-400 mt-10">
      Ready for the real thing? <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/1512.05813"><img src="/reading/arxiv.webp" alt="arxiv" style="display:inline;height:1em;vertical-align:-0.1em;margin-right:0.2em;"/> Read the paper</a>. Start at §2 for effectus categories, §4 for states and effects, §6 for the Born rule.
    </div>

    <p class="text-sm text-gray-500 mt-6">Framework connection: Effects as fuzzy predicates model the Natural Framework's Filter stage, a probabilistic gate that passes or blocks data. (<a href="https://june.kim/the-natural-framework"><img src="/reading/jk.png" alt="jk" style="display:inline;height:1em;vertical-align:-0.1em;margin-right:0.2em;"/>The Natural Framework</a>)</p>

